A '''blotting matrix''', in [[molecular biology]] and [[genetics]], is the substrate onto which [[macromolecules]], such as [[proteins]], are transferred in a [[Blot (biology)|blot]] method.<ref name="Kurien">{{cite book|editor=Biji T. Kurien|others=R. Hal Scofield|title=Protein Blotting and Detection|year=2009|publisher=Humana Press|location=New York|isbn=1934115738}}</ref> The matrices are generally chemically modified paper filters or microporous membrane filters. In a [[dot blot]], macromolecules are applied directly to the matrix. Macromolecules can also be separated and transferred via [[gel electrophoresis]].<ref name="Kurien"/>

One of the most common blotting matrices for protein analysis is [[nitrocellulose]], which has a high affinity for proteins due to hydrophobic interactions. However, proteins with low molecular weight have a small affinity for nitrocellulose, limiting potential applications. This defect may be remedied by [[glutaraldehyde]], which can covalently bond proteins to nitrocellulose. Another matrix is [[cellulose]] paper modified with diazophenylthiother, which can also facilitate covalent bonding of proteins. Nylon membranes are also used for protein blotting, although they may result in the binding of anionic dyes such as [[Coomassie blue]] and [[Amido black]]. [[Polyvinylidene fluoride]] membranes are also commonly used, due to their hydrophobicity.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Carl R. |last1=Merril |first2=Karen M. |last2=Washart|title=Gel Electrophoresis of Proteins|url=http://www.aun.edu.eg/molecular_biology/Protein%20workshop/Hames_Gel%20Electrophoresis%20of%20Proteins-A%20Practical%20Approach%203rd%20ed.pdf|date=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=71}}</ref>

