In&nbsp;cryptography, a&nbsp;'''client certificate'''&nbsp;is a type of&nbsp;[[digital certificate]]&nbsp;that is used by&nbsp;[[Client (computing)|client systems]]&nbsp;to make authenticated requests to a remote&nbsp;[[Server (computing)|server]].<ref>{{Cite IETF|rfc = 5246|section = 7.4.4|year = 2008|last1 = Dierks|first1 = T.|last2 = Rescorla|first2 = E.|month = August|accessdate = 29 October 2014}}</ref> Client certificates play a key role in many&nbsp;[[mutual authentication]]&nbsp;designs, providing strong assurances of a requester's identity.
